===============================================================================
DISTRIBUTED WEB INFRASTRUCTURE - EXPLANATION
===============================================================================

To view the diagram of the distributed infrastructure, click here:
https://imgur.com/8i5AqqZ

===============================================================================

## STEP 1: REQUEST AND DNS RESOLUTION

The user types "www.foobar.com" in the browser. The browser queries the DNS
(Domain Name System) which translates the domain name into the public IP
address of the Load Balancer (HAProxy).

## STEP 2: THE LOAD BALANCER (HAProxy)

The Load Balancer receives the HTTP request on port 80. Its role is to
distribute the incoming traffic between the two application servers (Server 1
and Server 2) so neither is overloaded.

- ALGORITHM: By default, it is configured with the ROUND-ROBIN algorithm.
  It works as a turn-by-turn system: the 1st request goes to Server 1, the
  2nd to Server 2, the 3rd to Server 1, and so on.
- CLUSTER SETUP: HAProxy manages two web servers working at the same time,
  which means this is an ACTIVE-ACTIVE setup. (In an Active-Passive setup,
  one server is active while the other is on standby, only turning on if the
  first one fails).

## STEP 3: WEB AND APPLICATION SERVERS (Server 1 & Server 2)

The Load Balancer forwards the request to one of the two servers. On that
server, the Nginx WEB SERVER receives the request and passes it to the
APPLICATION SERVER, which executes the code (codebase).

## STEP 4: DATABASE CLUSTER (Primary-Replica / Master-Slave)

The infrastructure uses a MySQL database cluster designed to optimize data
handling and synchronization:

- PRIMARY NODE (Master): The Application Server sends all WRITE requests
  (e.g., creating an account, updating a profile, adding a post) exclusively
  to the Primary node. It is the only source of truth for data modifications.
- REPLICA NODE (Slave): The Application Server sends all READ requests
  (e.g., viewing a page, reading a post, browsing profiles) to the Replica
  node. The Replica continuously synchronizes and duplicates data from the
  Primary node in real-time.

===============================================================================
ISSUES WITH THIS INFRASTRUCTURE
===============================================================================

1. SPOF (Single Points of Failure):

- The Load Balancer (HAProxy) is a SPOF. If this single machine crashes,
  no user can access the website anymore, even if the backend servers work.
- The Primary Database is a SPOF. If it goes down, the application cannot
  write or save any new data because the Replica can only handle read operations
  and cannot take over automatically.

2. SECURITY ISSUES:

- No HTTPS: Data is transmitted in clear text over port 80, making it
  vulnerable to interception or cyberattacks.
- No Firewall: There is no security barrier to filter incoming traffic and
  block unauthorized access to private server ports.

3. NO MONITORING:

- There are no tools (like DataDog or Uptime Robot) to track server metrics
  (CPU, RAM, disk usage) or application health. We won't know if the system
  slows down or crashes unless a user reports it.
